<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="2939" pageId="5" pageNumber="2938" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[494,803,1432,1489]" box="[561,737,1465,1489]" pageId="5" pageNumber="2938">
(
<figureCitation box="[568,698,1465,1489]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="5.[125,185,1025,1044]" captionTargetBox="[128,1173,163,986]" captionTargetId="figure-110@5.[125,1173,133,989]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 1. Lycaenid butterfly species investigated showing male dorsal wing surfaces. (A) Penaincisalia aurulenta Johnson, 1990 (Peru: PN Huascarán, Quebrada Demanda; HNHM); (B) Penaincisalia perezi Bálint, 2001 (Peru: PN Husacarán; Llanganuco; HNHM paratype); (C) Penaincisalia culminicola (Staudinger, 1894) (Peru: PNB Huascarán, Llanganuco; HNHM); (D) Thecloxurina loxurina (Felder and Felder, 1865) (Ecuador: Carchi, Res. Forest. Golondrinas; HNHM); (E) Thecloxurina atymna (Hewitson, 1870) (Ecuador: Zamora, Cord. Lagunillas; HNHM); (F) Thecloxurina atymna (Hewitson, 1870) (Ecuador: Azuay, Cuenca; HNHM)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5219996" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5219996/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="2938">Figures 1A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[712,728,1465,1489]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="7.[125,185,910,929]" captionTargetBox="[125,1173,133,874]" captionTargetId="figure-186@7.[125,1173,133,874]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 2. Scanning electron micrographs of Penaincisalia aurulenta scale microstructures. (A) Tile- and shovelshaped scales with dentate anterior margins; (B) longitudinal ridges with flutes, straight cross ribs; (C) widely open microcells, wispy internal structures; (D) widely open microcells, deep-laying pepper-pot structures." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5219998" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5219998/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="2938">2</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[125,1173,1530,1684]" lastBlockId="6.[138,1185,912,1066]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="2939" pageId="5" pageNumber="2938">
The dorsal colour is Burnt Orange without iridescence (
<figureCitation box="[788,907,1530,1554]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="5.[125,185,1025,1044]" captionTargetBox="[128,1173,163,986]" captionTargetId="figure-110@5.[125,1173,133,989]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 1. Lycaenid butterfly species investigated showing male dorsal wing surfaces. (A) Penaincisalia aurulenta Johnson, 1990 (Peru: PN Huascarán, Quebrada Demanda; HNHM); (B) Penaincisalia perezi Bálint, 2001 (Peru: PN Husacarán; Llanganuco; HNHM paratype); (C) Penaincisalia culminicola (Staudinger, 1894) (Peru: PNB Huascarán, Llanganuco; HNHM); (D) Thecloxurina loxurina (Felder and Felder, 1865) (Ecuador: Carchi, Res. Forest. Golondrinas; HNHM); (E) Thecloxurina atymna (Hewitson, 1870) (Ecuador: Zamora, Cord. Lagunillas; HNHM); (F) Thecloxurina atymna (Hewitson, 1870) (Ecuador: Azuay, Cuenca; HNHM)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5219996" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5219996/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="2938">Figure 1A</figureCitation>
). The scales are tile- or shovel-shaped with a toothed anterior margin. The length/width ratio of tile-shaped scales is 3/ 1 (120/ 
<quantity box="[204,282,1593,1619]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="2938" unit="mm" value="40.0">40 mm</quantity>
). The shovel-shaped scales are shorter and wider (length/width52/1, 80/ 
<quantity box="[1083,1159,1593,1619]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="2938" unit="mm" value="40.0">40 mm</quantity>
). The dentation of the tile-shaped scales is deeper (
<figureCitation box="[728,849,1628,1652]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="7.[125,185,910,929]" captionTargetBox="[125,1173,133,874]" captionTargetId="figure-186@7.[125,1173,133,874]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 2. Scanning electron micrographs of Penaincisalia aurulenta scale microstructures. (A) Tile- and shovelshaped scales with dentate anterior margins; (B) longitudinal ridges with flutes, straight cross ribs; (C) widely open microcells, wispy internal structures; (D) widely open microcells, deep-laying pepper-pot structures." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5219998" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5219998/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="2938">Figure 2A</figureCitation>
). We could not detect any qualitative difference between the microstructures of the 
<specimenCount box="[755,864,1660,1684]" pageId="5" pageNumber="2938" type="generic" typeStatus="types">two types</specimenCount>
. The longitudinal ridges are parallel and low, with flutes. The space (5length of the microcells) between the ridges is approximately 
<quantity box="[308,369,943,969]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="2939" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
. Cross ribs are straight, their intervals are slightly irregular and less than 
<quantity box="[138,221,975,1001]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="2939" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.5 mm</quantity>
. The microcells are oblong or rectangular and widely open (
<figureCitation box="[953,1111,977,1001]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="7.[125,185,910,929]" captionTargetBox="[125,1173,133,874]" captionTargetId="figure-186@7.[125,1173,133,874]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 2. Scanning electron micrographs of Penaincisalia aurulenta scale microstructures. (A) Tile- and shovelshaped scales with dentate anterior margins; (B) longitudinal ridges with flutes, straight cross ribs; (C) widely open microcells, wispy internal structures; (D) widely open microcells, deep-laying pepper-pot structures." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5219998" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5219998/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="2939">Figure 2B, C</figureCitation>
). The nanostructures are irregularly fragmented and sparse or lost with the trabeculae, and the reverse surface of the scale can be clearly seen at higher magnification (
<figureCitation box="[941,1064,1042,1066]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="7.[125,185,910,929]" captionTargetBox="[125,1173,133,874]" captionTargetId="figure-186@7.[125,1173,133,874]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 2. Scanning electron micrographs of Penaincisalia aurulenta scale microstructures. (A) Tile- and shovelshaped scales with dentate anterior margins; (B) longitudinal ridges with flutes, straight cross ribs; (C) widely open microcells, wispy internal structures; (D) widely open microcells, deep-laying pepper-pot structures." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5219998" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5219998/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="2939">Figure 2D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
